ownedComment.body: We can scale horizontally with as many of these nodes and serving interfaces we might need. Scaling should be done by the cloud (Google's or Amazon's) in terms of more memory, more processors and more machines. This design will scale with the demand.
Here goes the description for just the current API PoC
This Docker Image, now, has all the APIs for the staff, for the movies; the ones that are transactional and the ones that does just querying.
We could put every replica in separates Kubernetes nodes; if the case demand, we can scale it like that.
These two will communicate throught simple sockets by Spring Data. Current provided PoC might not be so different from this in overall terms.
This server will expose the services for every external mobile, system or website to consume.
Note that the track for Staff and Movie runs separated. We made this early design decission in case we need to put every set of services in their own Docker Image

The Staff Controller is thinner than the Movie one. Granted. But it is for a reason that we separated those methods. We do not know yet how the users of the app will desire it to grow, if the avanique of attributes and edges ends being here, we might want it to run in a separated image from the Movie's one.

Repository Layer
This layer aim is to provide access to persistent data structures. At this time, what we want is to manage a Graph Database.
We use Spring Boot Data for that intent.

Several methods has been overloaded. The intention is to allow the forward/backward compatibility of the api. As it evolves, there could be new attributes that may appear for every kind of node. This flexibility will allow it to grow indefinitly; we transpired Neo4J schemeless philosophy.

documentation.value: Saves the staff node as is. NOTE: just for the sake of simplicity, here we do it checking that the name is unique, before we add it. This is different approach to what we showed in Movies; I'm reluctant to do it because it implies that the names are the node identifiers, which is not true. We should instruct the API to operate with a rigurous ID that must be provided by the consumer before it sends a request.
